to give rights to agencies like
the Library of Congress that are

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:47.820
in the business of
digital preservation.

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:50.170
We have this fair use
notion here in the US

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:54.870
and I think a preservation
arrangement also ought

00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:57.120
to be incorporated
into our thinking.

00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:01.560
And finally, we need business
models to retain this vast

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:05.740
and increasing amount of digital
content over long periods of time.

00:15:05.740 --> 00:15:07.470
And here I'm not talking
about decades,

00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:09.440
I'm talking about centuries.

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:12.770
And business models for
centuries are hard to come by.

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:15.540 position:56%
I can think of a few, there are some
breweries that have been around for

00:15:15.540 --> 00:15:17.200
about 4 or 500 hundred years.

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:22.530
And of course, there's always
the Catholic Church so, anyway.

00:15:22.530 --> 00:15:24.800
The other thing which I
find very interesting is

00:15:24.800 --> 00:15:30.420
that the OAIS definitions that
I'm sure you're all familiar

00:15:30.420 --> 00:15:32.870
with have this interesting
recursive property

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:37.690 position:56%
that you know you have these digital
representations of the objects

00:15:37.690 --> 00:15:42.450
that you're preserving and there
are recursive references to this

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:44.750
until you get down to the point

00:15:44.750 --> 00:15:50.330 position:56%
where there's some specific group
whose domain knowledge is sufficient

00:15:50.330 --> 00:15:54.100
to correctly interpret the content
that's being preserved and at

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:56.320
that point has to stop somewhere.

00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:58.080
But the problem is the groups

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:02.150
that understand the details
may eventually die out,

00:16:02.150 --> 00:16:05.970
in which case we may have to recur
once more in order to make sure

00:16:05.970 --> 00:16:09.570
that subsequent users
have enough information

00:16:09.570 --> 00:16:11.670
to correctly interpret the content.

00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:14.200
So, there's a lot of
formality hiding in here,

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:15.580
but it's going to be necessary.

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:19.690
And of course, we'll have to
have all kinds of specializations

00:16:19.690 --> 00:16:23.310
for representations for
particular kinds of data

00:16:23.310 --> 00:16:27.370
and I include not simply documents
that you would typically find here

00:16:27.370 --> 00:16:30.380
in this library, but also
scientific data, data collection

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:33.560
from space missions at
NASA and data coming

00:16:33.560 --> 00:16:34.900
from the large hadron collider.

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:40.000
All of that stuff is digital
content worthy of preservation.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.510
So, it needs to by systematic.

00:16:42.510 --> 00:16:47.780
I'm not necessarily arguing that
the OAIS concepts are the only ones

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:49.210
that can be applied here.

00:16:49.210 --> 00:16:52.460
But, they certainly are
representative of the style

00:16:52.460 --> 00:16:54.720
that I think is necessary.

00:16:54.720 --> 00:17:00.040
And within our own
research organizations here

00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:05.530
in the United States, PCAST and
the OSTP have strongly recommended

00:17:05.530 --> 00:17:10.930 position:56%
that research sponsored by the US
government should incorporate saving

00:17:10.930 --> 00:17:16.410
of the data, software and metadata
associated with that research

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:19.430
so that it can be made
available in perpetuity

00:17:19.430 --> 00:17:22.630
to the future researchers.

00:17:22.630 --> 00:17:26.740 position:56%
I also think that if we're going to
build archives, we better build more

00:17:26.740 --> 00:17:30.400
than one for the possibility
that only one goes away

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:31.740
and then everything is lost.

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:35.110
So, distributing the information

00:17:35.110 --> 00:17:38.910
across multiple archives
strikes me as a wise move.

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:41.700
And finally, we need
policy frameworks

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:45.830
that will provide incentives
for people to build

00:17:45.830 --> 00:17:48.350
and operate these archives.

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:50.080
So, let me switch gears
for a moment.

00:17:50.080 --> 00:17:54.630
Move into some of the more
substantive questions.

00:17:54.630 --> 00:17:57.900
One of them has to do with
how we archive static content.

00:17:57.900 --> 00:18:00.780
Some of you will notice
that there are certain media

00:18:00.780 --> 00:18:03.950
that are blasted for
quite a long time.

00:18:03.950 --> 00:18:08.790
By accident in some cases like
these cuneiform tablets that were,

00:18:08.790 --> 00:18:11.570
you know essentially made on clay.

00:18:11.570 --> 00:18:15.480
Most of them were intended to be
reused, except the fires burned

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:19.980
down some of the archives and baked
the clay into its permanent form.

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:21.660
Which is why we still
have some of them.

00:18:21.660 --> 00:18:27.210 position:56%
Now, what I don't like about this is
preservation by accident [laugther].

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:30.490
I think that those of us in this
room should be paying attention

00:18:30.490 --> 00:18:35.000
to preservation on purpose and we
should have ways of doing that.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.860
Now, we've also seen
other documents.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:40.760
Vellum for example is
quite a resilient material.

00:18:40.760 --> 00:18:43.740 position:56%
Which is why I thought the term
digital vellum captured a little bit

00:18:43.740 --> 00:18:45.070
of that notion.

00:18:45.070 --> 00:18:48.730 position:56%
Unfortunately, I think that to
preserve all the digital information

00:18:48.730 --> 00:18:52.280
on real vellum, it would
require a lot of goats and sheep.

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:55.270
And more than exist
even in New Zealand.

00:18:55.270 --> 00:19:00.760
So, we need to do something
comparable with different media.

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:04.220
And we've all seen the accidental
preservation of [inaudible]

00:19:04.220 --> 00:19:07.610
for example, because it happened
to have been stored in a cave

00:19:07.610 --> 00:19:09.950
in a dessert where it was dry.

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:13.320
But, again, I don't want
preservation by accident.

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:18.000
Now, when digital technologies
emerged over the past 70 years,

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.500
people got very excited
because bits seemed

00:19:20.500 --> 00:19:23.900
to have this ethereal
ability to just live forever.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:26.190
After all, they're just
logical bits, right?

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:29.960
But they actually have
physical manifestations.

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:34.000
And I will tell you showing up here
at the Library of Congress a decade

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.950
and a half ago with some CD-ROMs,

00:19:37.950 --> 00:19:39.900
thinking look at all
the data we can store

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:41.460
on such a small amount of space.

00:19:41.460 --> 00:19:43.520
I'm so proud of myself.

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:49.610
And one of the librarians here
came back with a vellum manuscript.

00:19:49.610 --> 00:19:54.570
It was 1000 years old, and still
as readable today as it was then.

00:19:54.570 --> 00:20:00.190
And if you happen to speak, you
know in ancient Greek, etcetera.

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:06.410 position:56%
And she said to me, and how long
will your polycarbonate CD-ROM last?

00:20:06.410 --> 00:20:09.500
And of course, I didn't have
a very good answer for that.

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:12.660
It might only be 20 years
before it delaminates.

00:20:12.660 --> 00:20:15.090
But the more severe
problem is that the reader

00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:17.620
for it might not be
available for it either.

00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:19.270
Not even in the Smithsonian,

00:20:19.270 --> 00:20:21.370
or if it is it might
not be in workable form.

00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:27.250
So, you see all these examples
of media that have come and gone.

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:29.970
If you buy Macintosh
equipment like I do,

00:20:29.970 --> 00:20:31.550 position:56%
you might have regretted discovering

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:34.460
that the latest versions don't
have a CD-ROM reader in them

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:36.870
at all to save space I guess.

00:20:36.870 --> 00:20:38.730
But it means that my stack of media

00:20:38.730 --> 00:20:41.780
that I carefully accumulated
is no longer useful

00:20:41.780 --> 00:20:43.150
because I can't read it.

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:44.450
So, that's a serious problem.

00:20:44.450 --> 00:20:45.750
And it gets worse.

00:20:45.750 --> 00:20:49.020
I mean we have all these
other media, like YouTube,

00:20:49.020 --> 00:20:50.680
and Flickr and Picasa and so on.

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:52.460
All these online media.

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:56.440
So, what I tell other audiences,
you know this as well as anyone,

00:20:56.440 --> 00:21:00.100
but I try to give them a sense
for why this is important.

00:21:00.100 --> 00:21:03.420
So, those of you, I hope who
have read, "A Team of Rivals"

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:08.590
by Doris Kearns Goodwin will have
noticed how well she reproduced the

00:21:08.590 --> 00:21:10.150
conversations of the time.

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:12.650
It felt like she had
been a fly on the wall,

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:15.420
although we knew she
wasn't there in the 1860s.

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:16.720
So, how did she do that?

00:21:16.720 --> 00:21:18.980
Well she ran around to I
don't know how many libraries.

00:21:18.980 --> 00:21:21.580
I put 100 down here
just as a placeholder.

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:26.070
But she got the correspondence
of the principles in this story.

00:21:26.070 --> 00:21:27.660
So, she knew what they
were talking about

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:31.070
and how they expressed themselves,
and what positions they took.

00:21:31.070 --> 00:21:33.950
And she was able to
reproduce the conversations

00:21:33.950 --> 00:21:36.370
in what I thought was
a very credible way.

00:21:36.370 --> 00:21:40.070
So, imagine that you're a 22nd
century Doris Kearns Goodwin

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:42.810
and you're trying to
reproduce the tenner

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:45.680
of the times in the 21st century.

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:47.110
What will she find.

00:21:47.110 --> 00:21:50.230
You know will the National
Archives have anything useful

00:21:50.230 --> 00:21:51.530
to share with us?

00:21:51.530 --> 00:21:53.290
What about all the
emails and the Tweets,

00:21:53.290 --> 00:21:55.770
and the blogs and everything else.

00:21:55.770 --> 00:22:00.650
Will any of that be
render-able in the 22nd century.

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:02.470
And the answer is we don't know.

00:22:02.470 --> 00:22:05.950
And I think that we don't have
very good answers at this point.

00:22:05.950 --> 00:22:07.670
And it gets even more complicated.

00:22:07.670 --> 00:22:12.250
When you think about executable
content, this is not static stuff.

00:22:12.250 --> 00:22:14.720
This requires interpretation
by software.

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:16.030
People are interacting with it.

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:17.540
It's not just games.

00:22:17.540 --> 00:22:21.070
I mean there are other
kinds of applications too.

00:22:21.070 --> 00:22:25.560
Things like spreadsheets and so on,
which are things you interact with.

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:29.030
A static version of the
spreadsheet is typically a snapshot

00:22:29.030 --> 00:22:30.330
of its current values.

00:22:30.330 --> 00:22:33.390
But the value of the spreadsheet is
the ability to put different values

00:22:33.390 --> 00:22:35.880
in and have software run.

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:39.630
So, we have this executable
content that we have to think

00:22:39.630 --> 00:22:44.000
about in the archival context.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.580 position:56%
So, there are a bunch of challenges.

00:22:46.580 --> 00:22:49.080
And I suppose over the last
few days, you've been talking

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:51.320
about these and others,
but I will remind you

00:22:51.320 --> 00:22:53.290
of the ones that come to my mind.

00:22:53.290 --> 00:22:55.900
One is figuring out what
the bits mean at all.

00:22:55.900 --> 00:22:58.140
The second one is the
metadata capture.

00:22:58.140 --> 00:23:01.590
The third is hanging on to
executable code or source code

00:23:01.590 --> 00:23:04.210
if we can get it and
then it's this question

00:23:04.210 --> 00:23:07.510
of how do I figure out
how to run old code.

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:12.650
And I've been using kind
of sort of a metaphor here.

00:23:12.650 --> 00:23:16.160
If you could take a
digital x-ray of a computer

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:20.900
when it has the operating system,
the application, the actual files

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:23.450
that its working on
plus the hardware,

00:23:23.450 --> 00:23:27.310
and you could take a snapshot of
all that and then re-instantiate it

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:30.530
by emulating the hardware and
running the old operating system

00:23:30.530 --> 00:23:32.420
and putting the application on it.

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:35.510
You might actually be able
to preserve the capability

00:23:35.510 --> 00:23:38.470
to run all this old software
over long periods of time.

00:23:38.470 --> 00:23:41.970
Of course, you also have to have a
place to store all of this stuff.

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:47.880
So, we have to have
affordable large scale memory.

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:52.450
Now, unfortunately, we live in a
world which is filled with change.

00:23:52.450 --> 00:23:53.750
And one of the things is

00:23:53.750 --> 00:23:55.710
that companies don't
necessarily last forever.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:23:57.380
So, they go bankrupt.

00:23:57.380 --> 00:23:59.760
And some of their assets
turn out to be things

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:01.060
that get sold to other people.

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:04.680
So, if a company goes bankrupt
that made the application software

00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:07.910 position:56%
that you use to produce new content,

00:24:07.910 --> 00:24:10.960
and you say after the company
goes bankrupt, can I have a copy

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:12.920
of the program, can I
have the source code?

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:15.220
And the bankruptcy judge
says no unless you want

00:24:15.220 --> 00:24:18.520
to pay $6 million for this asset.

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:21.940
So, or you have companies that just
say I can't support this anymore.

00:24:21.940 --> 00:24:23.480
I'm not going to make it run.

00:24:23.480 --> 00:24:28.130 position:56%
It, being an application, run on
the current day's operating systems,

00:24:28.130 --> 00:24:29.580
or next year's operating systems.

00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:32.180
And now you're stuck,
because either you have

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:35.240
to keep using the old operating
system to use the old application,

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:39.310
or you have to hope somebody
can translate the documents

00:24:39.310 --> 00:24:42.510
that you've produced, or the
object you produced into something

00:24:42.510 --> 00:24:44.470
that het new software
will interpret.

00:24:44.470 --> 00:24:46.770
And we know that not everybody
is going to pay attention

00:24:46.770 --> 00:24:48.720
to backward compatibility.

00:24:48.720 --> 00:24:51.240 position:56%
So, there are really tough problems.

00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:56.370
So, there's questions about who
owns the software in addition

00:24:56.370 --> 00:24:58.290
to who owns the digital objects.

00:24:58.290 --> 00:25:02.620
And under which circumstances
you have access to that software.

00:25:02.620 --> 00:25:05.580
And so again I keep thinking
we need legal frameworks

00:25:05.580 --> 00:25:08.920
that provide exceptions
for preservation purposes.

00:25:08.920 --> 00:25:12.380
So, there is a project at
Carnegie Mellon, which I hope some

00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:14.530
of you may already know
about, called Olive,

00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:18.070
which is like the thing you
put in your cocktail glass.

00:25:18.070 --> 00:25:22.000
This is being run, or was
run under in a self-support

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.890
by Mahadev Satyanarayanan.

00:25:24.890 --> 00:25:27.530
We call him Satya for
obvious reasons.

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:30.760
And this was a very
successful effort

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:33.100
to essentially emulate old hardware

00:25:33.100 --> 00:25:35.770
and run old operating
systems on the system.

00:25:35.770 --> 00:25:38.230
Now, this is not easy.

00:25:38.230 --> 00:25:40.100
It might sound like
it's easy, but it's not.

00:25:40.100 --> 00:25:42.750
There's a whole lot of thing
that have to be emulated

00:25:42.750 --> 00:25:45.830
or correctly identified
in order to make it work.

00:25:45.830 --> 00:25:48.540
One of them is making sure you
understand exactly how the old

00:25:48.540 --> 00:25:51.980
hardware works so you
can emulate exactly how

00:25:51.980 --> 00:25:56.880
that hardware executes instructions
on a virtual environment.

00:25:56.880 --> 00:25:59.110
Then you have to be able to
bring in the operating system

00:25:59.110 --> 00:26:01.120
and the applications and so on.

00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:05.080 position:56%
And that includes all the library's
executable libraries that are needed

00:26:05.080 --> 00:26:07.060
to make the applications work.

00:26:07.060 --> 00:26:08.410
So, it just goes on and on.

00:26:08.410 --> 00:26:10.740
Language settings have to
be known I mean like what

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:12.930
if this is an application
that was you know written

00:26:12.930 --> 00:26:17.140
for Bulgarian instead of English
or French, or something else.

00:26:17.140 --> 00:26:20.530
So, there's a whole lot of
details that have to be remembered

00:26:20.530 --> 00:26:23.810
and replicated in order
to make this stuff work.

00:26:23.810 --> 00:26:27.950
And that's why this term digital
x-ray seemed so attractive.

00:26:27.950 --> 00:26:32.060
Now, what was very interesting
is that he said well, all right.

00:26:32.060 --> 00:26:38.720
So, I'm going ingest into
this space of preservation all

00:26:38.720 --> 00:26:42.200
of the description of hardware,
all of the operating system,

00:26:42.200 --> 00:26:45.370
all the executable libraries,
all of the application.

00:26:45.370 --> 00:26:49.070
Plus, the actual object that's
being interpreted and incorporate

00:26:49.070 --> 00:26:52.300
that into a great big bundle
and run it as a virtual,

00:26:52.300 --> 00:26:53.950
in a virtual machine environment.

00:26:53.950 --> 00:26:59.690
And in his first work he did
this on laptop, that was capable

00:26:59.690 --> 00:27:01.820
of emulating other hardware.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:06.840
But he had an idea that this is so,
these virtual machines are so big,

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:09.790
that he ought to find
some alternative way

00:27:09.790 --> 00:27:12.300
of running the software and
then having to draw it all

00:27:12.300 --> 00:27:14.410
into one box all at once.

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:18.910
So, he got this idea about
using this streaming video,

00:27:18.910 --> 00:27:23.250
which all of us see on YouTube and
other applications as a metaphor

00:27:23.250 --> 00:27:26.140
for pulling only that
which is needed

00:27:26.140 --> 00:27:30.070
from this gigantic virtual machine
into the executing environment.

00:27:30.070 --> 00:27:35.840
And so, it's sort of like a paging
system in a time-shared machine.

00:27:35.840 --> 00:27:37.900
So, it's actually not
too easy though.

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:41.640
In the case of streaming video,
it's pretty well ordered.

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:43.150
You just pull in the next frame.

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:44.750
And if you want to get a
little ahead of the game,

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:47.510
you pull in a few more
frames ahead of time so that

00:27:47.510 --> 00:27:51.400
if there's some stuttering in the
network you don't see a flicker

00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:54.580
in the video or a stutter
in the audio.

00:27:54.580 --> 00:27:59.320 position:56%
But in the case of a virtual machine
execution, if you're taking pages

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:02.450
of software in, the
program jumps around.

00:28:02.450 --> 00:28:05.210
And so, the pages that are
needed are not necessarily just

00:28:05.210 --> 00:28:06.840
in simple sequential order.

00:28:06.840 --> 00:28:10.680
So, you have to be pretty
clever about drawing in pieces

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:14.470
of the virtual machine as
needed in order to execute that.

00:28:14.470 --> 00:28:18.690
So, he basically uses demand
paging, which is to say

00:28:18.690 --> 00:28:21.980
if you're executing a piece of code
and it needs to get to another part

00:28:21.980 --> 00:28:25.920
of the executable program, you just
pull the page in when it's needed,

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:29.360 position:56%
but then you try to watch what the
patterns are and you pre-fetch pages

00:28:29.360 --> 00:28:32.080
to avoid delay in order
to make this work.

00:28:32.080 --> 00:28:34.630
So, I know that you don't want
to dive, I assume you don't want

00:28:34.630 --> 00:28:36.690
to dive too deep into all this.

00:28:36.690 --> 00:28:39.870
So, I'm not going to talk
about every single layer

00:28:39.870 --> 00:28:41.800
in this architecture,
except to say that it's

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:43.550 position:56%
like any other conventional machine,

00:28:43.550 --> 00:28:46.360
except you run a virtual
machine kernel

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:50.330
so that it can emulate
the hardware of machines

00:28:50.330 --> 00:28:51.630
that are no longer available,

00:28:51.630 --> 00:28:55.040
and then you run the operating
system inside of that environment

00:28:55.040 --> 00:29:00.940
and then run the application so
the virtual machine image has all

00:29:00.940 --> 00:29:04.600
of this stuff that's needed
and it's expressed in XML

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:07.210
so this looks like
a web application.

00:29:07.210 --> 00:29:10.740
So, you can imagine simply
running on a computer connected

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:14.990 position:56%
to the internet something that looks
like it's connected to a server

00:29:14.990 --> 00:29:17.530
on the Worldwide Web and
it's pulling in XML pages,

00:29:17.530 --> 00:29:21.740
but in fact what it's doing is
running this virtual machine.

00:29:21.740 --> 00:29:25.670
So, this is sort of an
image of what it looks like.

00:29:25.670 --> 00:29:31.760
He's using the QEMU, QEMU
KVM kernel virtual machine.

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:34.600
And then, for example, he
was running Microsoft Windows

00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:37.410
and he was running an
app on top of that.

00:29:37.410 --> 00:29:40.400
He has a cache which
is the clean cache,

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:44.370
which hasn't experienced
any execution.

00:29:44.370 --> 00:29:48.690 position:56%
And then as the program runs, he
has to keep track of what's changed.

00:29:48.690 --> 00:29:50.640
And he goes out and pulls stuff in.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:54.750
So, the way this tends to work
is that you can even run this

00:29:54.750 --> 00:29:57.100
in such a way that the
virtual machine is not even

00:29:57.100 --> 00:29:59.120
on your desktop or laptop.

00:29:59.120 --> 00:30:03.320
It's actually running in the cloud.

00:30:03.320 --> 00:30:10.500
And the only thing that you
present to the client is the image.

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:13.170
Some of you may even remember
something called X Windows

00:30:13.170 --> 00:30:17.350
that was developed at MIT, which
had a similar kind of notion,

00:30:17.350 --> 00:30:20.990
you just displayed the bits that
were appropriate on the screen.

00:30:20.990 --> 00:30:23.800
And all the other execution,
including the generation

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:26.730
of the display was done
back in the server.

00:30:26.730 --> 00:30:30.200
So, we can certainly
consider doing that as well,

00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:34.060
in order to limit was is
needed on the client side.

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:38.350
So, we still have a long way
before we're done with all of this.

00:30:38.350 --> 00:30:42.520
For one thing, actually handling
this increasingly large virtual

00:30:42.520 --> 00:30:47.050
machine structure is not so
easy, and yet we are expanding,

00:30:47.050 --> 00:30:51.780 position:56%
those of us who build cloud systems,
Google and Microsoft, and IBM,

00:30:51.780 --> 00:30:56.890
and elsewhere, Amazon, are building
larger, and larger capacity systems

00:30:56.890 --> 00:30:59.860
with multicore processors
and more and more memory.

00:30:59.860 --> 00:31:03.210
But the hardest part seems to be
getting precession in the emulation

00:31:03.210 --> 00:31:08.070
of the hardware, including mistakes
that have been made I the hardware

00:31:08.070 --> 00:31:10.650
that the application
actually relied on,

00:31:10.650 --> 00:31:12.900
even though it was a bug
in the hardware design.

00:31:12.900 --> 00:31:15.310
And so, getting that
accurately is tricky.

00:31:15.310 --> 00:31:19.060
And not all machine designers
are necessarily willing to hand

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:22.890
out to you the details of
their hardware instruction set.

00:31:22.890 --> 00:31:26.340
And so, here's another example of
a kind of exception one would look

00:31:26.340 --> 00:31:28.640
for for preservation purposes.

00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:35.490 position:56%
I think just I won't go through this
list completely but the idea here is

00:31:35.490 --> 00:31:40.010
for us to recognize that
we're going to need expertise

00:31:40.010 --> 00:31:43.990
in the hardware space and
the operating system space.

00:31:43.990 --> 00:31:47.260
And if we're going to make
this a general-purpose notion,

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:49.510 position:56%
we have to ask ourselves will people

00:31:49.510 --> 00:31:51.530
who write operating
systems be willing

00:31:51.530 --> 00:31:53.510
to part with the source code?

00:31:53.510 --> 00:31:56.940
Will they be willing to make
available executable object code?

00:31:56.940 --> 00:31:59.250
Will they be willing to
do this on a regular basis

00:31:59.250 --> 00:32:00.940
for purposes of preservation?

00:32:00.940 --> 00:32:05.430
Will they allow execution
of the emulated hardware

00:32:05.430 --> 00:32:08.840
and the emulated operating
system for thousands of people

00:32:08.840 --> 00:32:11.250
and not necessarily
get paid for that.

00:32:11.250 --> 00:32:15.990
At some point the patents
expire, the other rights expire

00:32:15.990 --> 00:32:20.260
and the general public needs to
have access to these executables

00:32:20.260 --> 00:32:24.810 position:56%
if they're going to be able to
reference material which doesn't run

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:26.570
in any other environment.

00:32:26.570 --> 00:32:30.620 position:56%
This should be of personal concern
to those of you who produce content.

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:36.000 position:56%
Because if you experience, like I
have material produced 20 years ago,

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:38.230
that no longer is accessible.

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:41.380
I have PowerPoint slides from 1997

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:43.870
that don't run on today's
PowerPoint.

00:32:43.870 --> 00:32:47.160
And this is not a gratuitous dig at
Microsoft, I'm not expecting them

00:32:47.160 --> 00:32:50.690
to be able to run backward
compatibility for 20 years.

00:32:50.690 --> 00:32:53.730
But it's really a shock
when you pull up something

00:32:53.730 --> 00:32:58.030
that you worked hard on and realize
that it's not available anymore.

00:32:58.030 --> 00:33:00.630
And its content has been lost.

00:33:00.630 --> 00:33:06.360
And so, I actually kept an old IBM
ThinkPad around running Windows XP

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:09.040
and an old version of
Microsoft, that just happens

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:12.440
to reach far enough back
to pick up those pages,

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:14.640 position:56%
but I've had to reproduce the pages.

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:18.570
So, I want to turn now, so
this is one part of the story.

00:33:18.570 --> 00:33:21.510
And it's using virtual
machine technology in order

00:33:21.510 --> 00:33:24.750
to preserve executability
over a long period of time.

00:33:24.750 --> 00:33:27.940
But I want to turn now to
the self-archiving web idea.

00:33:27.940 --> 00:33:35.460
This notion was first introduced
to me last year by Tim Berners-Lee

00:33:35.460 --> 00:33:38.460
and David Reid and Brewster Kahle.

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:43.600
And their idea was that the
web is this femoral thing.

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:47.000
We all realize that the web
is what it is in the instant.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.510
It doesn't automatically
archive itself,

00:33:49.510 --> 00:33:52.110
it doesn't remember previous pages.

00:33:52.110 --> 00:33:57.090
And so, all we see when we
go online is today's web.

00:33:57.090 --> 00:34:00.290
We don't see yesterday's
web or yester year's web.

00:34:00.290 --> 00:34:01.590
And that's a pity.

00:34:01.590 --> 00:34:04.080
Because seeing things over a period

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:07.730
of time can often be
extremely illuminating.

00:34:07.730 --> 00:34:13.660 position:56%
I've been told more than once that
content that might be very important

00:34:13.660 --> 00:34:17.160
to understanding our
history may not appear

00:34:17.160 --> 00:34:19.630
to be important for
quite a long time.

00:34:19.630 --> 00:34:21.500
A hundred years, two hundred years.

00:34:21.500 --> 00:34:26.830 position:56%
Until finally we realize looking
back, this document, that decisions,

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:31.010
this website marked an
important moment in our history,

00:34:31.010 --> 00:34:32.650
but we didn't know that at the time

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:34.850
because we didn't have
enough perspective.

00:34:34.850 --> 00:34:39.200
And so, preservation of this
content is really important.

00:34:39.200 --> 00:34:41.250
So, I've been thinking
a lot about this.

00:34:41.250 --> 00:34:43.180
And I think the success

00:34:43.180 --> 00:34:46.790
of the internet might teach
us a few lessons about how

00:34:46.790 --> 00:34:49.670
to approach a self-archiving
web design.

00:34:49.670 --> 00:34:53.390
One of them is that collaboration
and cooperation were essential

00:34:53.390 --> 00:34:54.890
to the internet's evolution.

00:34:54.890 --> 00:34:57.470
Bob Kahn and I may
have started all this.

00:34:57.470 --> 00:35:00.590
But believe me it took millions
of people and still does

00:35:00.590 --> 00:35:06.980 position:56%
to keep the network going, and
growing, and changing, and evolving.

00:35:06.980 --> 00:35:10.710
And the atmosphere around
its creation invited that.

00:35:10.710 --> 00:35:12.530
It's a very open design.

00:35:12.530 --> 00:35:16.360
Anyone with an idea was free
to express that idea and try

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:18.870
to persuade others that they
should adopt those ideas.

00:35:18.870 --> 00:35:21.420
And in the internet
engineering task force

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:24.840
where the standards are
made, that process continues.

00:35:24.840 --> 00:35:29.270
Arguments are based on merit
not based on anything else.

00:35:29.270 --> 00:35:32.220
And if your ideas are
accepted they get implemented.

00:35:32.220 --> 00:35:33.520
And if they aren't they don't.

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:36.690
But the other thing
that was important is

00:35:36.690 --> 00:35:40.940
that we published the design
openly, without any restrictions,

00:35:40.940 --> 00:35:44.680
which is kind of amazing when you
consider this was done in 1973

00:35:44.680 --> 00:35:46.540
in the middle of the Cold War.

00:35:46.540 --> 00:35:50.630 position:56%
And we just published the details of
the architecture and the protocols.

00:35:50.630 --> 00:35:55.220
People have asked us how did
you get permission to do that?

00:35:55.220 --> 00:35:57.290
And the answer is,
well we didn't ask.

00:35:57.290 --> 00:36:00.240
But we had a rationale for it.

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:03.090
We said, okay we want
this to be available

00:36:03.090 --> 00:36:05.760
to the American Defense
Department so they don't have

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:09.710
to buy a particular brand of
machine in order to network them.

00:36:09.710 --> 00:36:14.690
Because back then we had SNA for
IBM, we had DECnet for digital.

00:36:14.690 --> 00:36:17.050
But we didn't think the Defense
Department should be forced

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:19.860
into buying only one brand
of machine to have network.

00:36:19.860 --> 00:36:23.020
So, we said let's do a
nonproprietary design.

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:26.960
And then we said, our allies will
probably need access to this too,

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:29.540
because we'll want them to be
able to interwork in a command

00:36:29.540 --> 00:36:31.900
and control system built on top.

00:36:31.900 --> 00:36:34.030
Then we said, well okay,
so who are our allies?

00:36:34.030 --> 00:36:37.020
And well, we could answer
that question in 1973.

00:36:37.020 --> 00:36:40.120
But we said, well who will
they be 25 years from now?

00:36:40.120 --> 00:36:41.420
And we weren't sure.

00:36:41.420 --> 00:36:44.580
We looked back 25 years and
realized that the allies of today,

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:49.680
that is '73, were different from
the ones, you know 25 years ago.

00:36:49.680 --> 00:36:53.850
So, we assumed that we would not
know who our allies were 25 years

00:36:53.850 --> 00:36:55.330
from now and since
this needed to work,

00:36:55.330 --> 00:36:57.210
we said everybody has
to be able to do it.

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:00.060
So, we just published openly
and said, if you can build stuff

00:37:00.060 --> 00:37:02.270
that works this way
and find somebody

00:37:02.270 --> 00:37:04.170
to connect to, it should work.

00:37:04.170 --> 00:37:07.270
And so, the internet grew in
a very organic way precisely

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:08.670
for that reason.

00:37:08.670 --> 00:37:11.960
We also said, we didn't care
what the business model was.

00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:14.320
And so, we said just,
it has to work this way,

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:15.980
but we don't care what
your business model is.

00:37:15.980 --> 00:37:19.200
So, we have nonprofit networks
and we have for profit networks,

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:21.590
government operated
networks, private networks

00:37:21.590 --> 00:37:25.170
like the ones you run at home with
your Wi-Fi service that connect

00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:26.470
into the rest of the internet.

00:37:26.470 --> 00:37:31.350
We were also very conscious of
hiding information among the layers

00:37:31.350 --> 00:37:34.240
of the architecture,
so that the IT packets

00:37:34.240 --> 00:37:36.040
or the internet protocol
packets didn't have

00:37:36.040 --> 00:37:37.910 position:56%
to know how they were being carried.

00:37:37.910 --> 00:37:41.680
So, new technology could be swept
in without changing that protocol.

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:43.980
We also said that the little
internet package should be

00:37:43.980 --> 00:37:45.280
pretty stupid.

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:46.580
They don't know what
they're carrying.

00:37:46.580 --> 00:37:48.640
All they know is they're
carrying bits.

00:37:48.640 --> 00:37:50.010
They don't know what the bits mean.

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:52.630
And that was good because if
you added a new application,

00:37:52.630 --> 00:37:55.880
all you had to do was reinterpret
the bits at the edges of the net.

00:37:55.880 --> 00:37:57.250
You didn't have to
change the network,

00:37:57.250 --> 00:37:59.580
because the network didn't
know and it didn't care.

00:37:59.580 --> 00:38:01.290
And so, this kind of modularity

00:38:01.290 --> 00:38:04.210
and information hiding
has been vastly helpful

00:38:04.210 --> 00:38:07.580
in allowing new applications
to be built on the network.

00:38:07.580 --> 00:38:12.040
And so of course out of many
one that is the internet.

00:38:12.040 --> 00:38:17.630
So, I gave a version of this
talk out at the Internet Archive,

00:38:17.630 --> 00:38:20.530
Brewster Kahle's operation,
which you should visit

00:38:20.530 --> 00:38:23.480
because it's an old
Christian Science Church,

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:26.320
and he even has the
pews are still there.

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:29.190
And in the back, he has
all the petabytes of memory

00:38:29.190 --> 00:38:31.480
that are stored away
with the flashing lights.

00:38:31.480 --> 00:38:33.570
And he has a whole
bunch of mannequins

00:38:33.570 --> 00:38:36.080
that are sitting on the pews.

00:38:36.080 --> 00:38:39.870
He moved them off to the right and
left so that we had our meeting,

00:38:39.870 --> 00:38:42.310
you know live people could
be sitting in the pews.

00:38:42.310 --> 00:38:44.830
I only accepted questions
from the mannequins

00:38:44.830 --> 00:38:46.520
on the left and the right.

00:38:46.520 --> 00:38:48.360
Safety measure.

00:38:48.360 --> 00:38:52.290
So, I've been thinking a
little bit about what kinds

00:38:52.290 --> 00:38:55.180
of technology we have to
incorporate into our thinking

00:38:55.180 --> 00:38:57.130
for our digital preservation.

00:38:57.130 --> 00:39:00.090
Compression schemes, in
order to use the, you know,

00:39:00.090 --> 00:39:06.390
lease amount of space, tarball
thing like that, which are common.

00:39:06.390 --> 00:39:13.380
And we need to store and
recover, up until now,

00:39:13.380 --> 00:39:14.680
this notion of compression

00:39:14.680 --> 00:39:17.790
and everything else involves
particular objects that get stored

00:39:17.790 --> 00:39:19.640
and then fully recovered.

00:39:19.640 --> 00:39:22.430
But the Worldwide Web is
a much more complex thing,

00:39:22.430 --> 00:39:24.700
because it's got pages
that point to other pages.

00:39:24.700 --> 00:39:27.140
It's a complex, it's a web.

00:39:27.140 --> 00:39:32.800
And so, figuring out how to
retain that part in addition

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:35.140
to the particular objects
is important.

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:39.980
So just preserving the webpage with
this HTML without the ability to go

00:39:39.980 --> 00:39:44.290
where the links went, or to
go to a place that replicates

00:39:44.290 --> 00:39:47.700
where the links went, means what we
have a very static representation

00:39:47.700 --> 00:39:50.710
of the net, we don't
understand its connectivity.

00:39:50.710 --> 00:39:55.880 position:56%
And we obviously have to think about
webpages that change over time.

00:39:55.880 --> 00:39:58.590
So, how do we keep track of
which versions we're looking at?

00:39:58.590 --> 00:40:02.160
The programmers do this all the
time with programmers' workbench

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:03.860
and things of that sorts.

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:07.740
So, this Worldwide Web is a
really complex reference structure

00:40:07.740 --> 00:40:10.420
so we have to deal with that.

00:40:10.420 --> 00:40:14.990
So, Brewster, Brewster Kahle has
been running the Internet Archive

00:40:14.990 --> 00:40:18.520
for at least 15 years,
maybe more, 20?

00:40:18.520 --> 00:40:25.610 position:56%
And it's taking snapshots of the
Worldwide Web and storing them away.

00:40:25.610 --> 00:40:27.050
It's indexed in time.

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:30.950
So, he has a way back machine that
lets you see what the web looked

00:40:30.950 --> 00:40:34.280
like at a certain year,
or a certain month.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:37.160
He also has to do something
with the hyperlinks.

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:39.710
Because it's pretty clear
that if you just copy the page

00:40:39.710 --> 00:40:43.590 position:56%
and its hyperlinks, 10 years from
now, or maybe even tomorrow clicking

00:40:43.590 --> 00:40:47.800 position:56%
on the link might fail because the
destination isn't available anymore.

00:40:47.800 --> 00:40:51.960 position:56%
So, he has to convert the hyperlinks
into something that he can point

00:40:51.960 --> 00:40:55.810
to inside the space of
his internet archive.

00:40:55.810 --> 00:40:59.750
So, he has to essentially
virtualize all of that.

00:40:59.750 --> 00:41:02.540
So, it's a self-contained system.

00:41:02.540 --> 00:41:05.770
And he has to be crawling the
web constantly, just like we do

00:41:05.770 --> 00:41:07.940
at Google to create the index.

00:41:07.940 --> 00:41:12.990
And then there's this
question of when is a page new?

00:41:12.990 --> 00:41:15.130
And you certainly wouldn't
want pages

00:41:15.130 --> 00:41:17.710
to be snapshot every time
you change one character.

00:41:17.710 --> 00:41:21.820
So, we have to have some kind of a
notion about publishing of a page,

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:25.510
saying I know what this page
version to be seen by everybody.

00:41:25.510 --> 00:41:28.580
So, that's an instant in time
that should mark when you want

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:31.500
to capture the web, that webpage.

00:41:31.500 --> 00:41:35.530
And then I keep thinking about
trying to capture everything that's

00:41:35.530 --> 00:41:38.940 position:56%
on the web, and I thought about that
philosophical problem do the set

00:41:38.940 --> 00:41:42.200
of all sets contain itself,
and I decided not to think

00:41:42.200 --> 00:41:44.920
about that anymore, because
it gave me a headache.

00:41:44.920 --> 00:41:48.840
So, I'm sorry you might
want to get a cup of coffee.

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:52.450
So, I worry also about the
amount of space required

00:41:52.450 --> 00:41:56.160
to retain the evolving
web, it's history,

00:41:56.160 --> 00:41:59.070
because it can barely
contain itself as it is.

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:01.240
I mean there's you know
all this space is taken

00:42:01.240 --> 00:42:02.600
up by all these webpages.

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:07.190
And so, there's this idea of
lots of copies keep things safe,

00:42:07.190 --> 00:42:12.620
but I'm kind of worried about how
much storage we actually can afford

00:42:12.620 --> 00:42:14.550 position:56%
to retain over long periods of time.

00:42:14.550 --> 00:42:17.910
So, we have to be thoughtful
about that.

00:42:17.910 --> 00:42:20.170
I'll come back to digital
object identifiers

00:42:20.170 --> 00:42:23.810
when I give me Vint Cerf
version of outcomes talk.

00:42:23.810 --> 00:42:28.260
And then there is this
other question about HTML,

00:42:28.260 --> 00:42:31.800
which itself has been evolving,
