00:42:36.590 --> 00:42:38.410
It's going to keep changing too.

00:42:38.410 --> 00:42:42.100
And so, whatever we do in terms of
archiving is going to have to take

00:42:42.100 --> 00:42:46.410
that into account because the
HTML of the webpage is just going

00:42:46.410 --> 00:42:51.350
to change over time and our ability
to interpret that is going to have

00:42:51.350 --> 00:42:55.450
to keep up with that evolutions,
and then I relay it back

00:42:55.450 --> 00:42:57.900
to permissions and access control.

00:42:57.900 --> 00:43:01.430
Some contents may be
access controlled now

00:43:01.430 --> 00:43:05.050
for copyright reasons,
or for monetary reasons.

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:09.980
And yet 100 years from now those
constraints may no longer be valid

00:43:09.980 --> 00:43:12.180
and we have to understand
when it's going

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:14.880
to be okay to make access open.

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:17.860
And so, this creates a
fairly complex environment,

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:22.680
where we literally have to keep
track of the access controls

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:28.320
and rights of every one of the
objects pointed to in the archive.

00:43:29.430 --> 00:43:34.240
So, I keep thinking about how
to make this more automatic.

00:43:34.240 --> 00:43:38.440
And one possibility is that
while you're creating webpages,

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:44.880
and launching them by saying I want
to publish, is that the environment

00:43:44.880 --> 00:43:48.510
that we use to say, oh and by
the way this page now needs

00:43:48.510 --> 00:43:50.500
to be archived.

00:43:50.500 --> 00:43:54.800
And can we make that kind of a
standard and cooperative practice?

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:58.320
I keep thinking about Google Docs
and one of the interesting things

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:01.130
about Google Docs is
that we replicate these

00:44:01.130 --> 00:44:05.180
