00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:50.670
which of the archives do we go
to when we make a page reference.

00:46:50.670 --> 00:46:53.760
And figuring out how to resolve

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:58.280
to multiple targets is
another part of this problem.

00:46:58.280 --> 00:47:00.060
Because there should
be multiple targets.

00:47:00.060 --> 00:47:04.020 position:56%
If I go to a particular webpage that
I'm trying to get to, I should have,

00:47:04.020 --> 00:47:09.060
the resolution system should
give me different choices

00:47:09.060 --> 00:47:11.980
because there should be multiple
places where I can go to get

00:47:11.980 --> 00:47:14.860
that content, otherwise
we're back at risk

00:47:14.860 --> 00:47:19.470
that that one place goes away.

00:47:19.470 --> 00:47:24.970
This, you know how newspapers, and
magazines and books are snapshots

00:47:24.970 --> 00:47:27.620
of a particular work in time.

00:47:27.620 --> 00:47:31.710
We have editions of newspapers;
we have editions of magazines.

00:47:31.710 --> 00:47:37.340
I kind of wonder at what rate
we should be snapshotting the

00:47:37.340 --> 00:47:38.700
Worldwide Web.

00:47:38.700 --> 00:47:40.310 position:56%
And I don't know the answer to that.

00:47:40.310 --> 00:47:41.610
Probably part of it is the rate

00:47:41.610 --> 00:47:44.750
at which things are changing
determine how often we

00:47:44.750 --> 00:47:46.050
