00:48:27.990 --> 00:48:31.210
do we have a way to mark it so that
if you're going in the archive,

00:48:31.210 --> 00:48:34.730
you don't accidentally ingest
a serious virus or something

00:48:34.730 --> 00:48:38.450
because you were out there
in the digital stacks?

00:48:38.450 --> 00:48:41.390
So, we may want that, you
know for history purposes

00:48:41.390 --> 00:48:44.170
to understand what the threats
were in this online environment,

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:46.140
but we also have to protect people.

00:48:46.140 --> 00:48:48.470
So, we have to recognize
what we're going.

00:48:48.470 --> 00:48:52.310
And then there's this
fidelity of the experience

00:48:52.310 --> 00:48:53.700
in the online environment.

00:48:53.700 --> 00:48:56.410
You know, one thing is just
to look at the webpage itself

00:48:56.410 --> 00:48:59.690
without actually being able
to execute any of the links.

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:02.920
But something deeper
than that is the ability

00:49:02.920 --> 00:49:05.120
to actually exercise the webpage

00:49:05.120 --> 00:49:09.030
as it would have been
when it was running.

00:49:09.030 --> 00:49:16.990
So, what happens once
a page is archived?

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:18.950 position:56%
Do we make sure that it's indelible?

00:49:18.950 --> 00:49:23.850 position:56%
Do we do digital signatures on it to
make sure that it can't be changed?

00:49:23.850 --> 00:49:25.500
That might turn out to be important

00:49:25.500 --> 00:49:28.480
because in a court case you
don't want somebody to say,

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:34.020
my webpage had the following
things on it in 1997, or 2005.

00:49:34.020 --> 00:49:35.800
But you can change it in order to,

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:38.500
you know modify the
court's decisions.

00:49:38.500 --> 00:49:41.830
You don't want that to happen
if you're going to attribute

00:49:41.830 --> 00:49:45.630
to the storage system
legal validity.

00:49:45.630 --> 00:49:51.830
What about if we make the
self-archiving web work,

00:49:51.830 --> 00:49:54.310
will some of the records be
considered official records

00:49:54.310 --> 00:49:57.770
like the ones that go
into the National Archive?

00:49:57.770 --> 00:50:00.430
What happens if the
content's encrypted?

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:01.730
So, now we have some problem

00:50:01.730 --> 00:50:04.000
because we can't see it
unless we have the keys,

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:05.750
but where do we store the keys?

00:50:05.750 --> 00:50:09.190
And who's responsible for
key management, and you know,

00:50:09.190 --> 00:50:11.980
anybody who's ever
forgotten their password,

00:50:11.980 --> 00:50:14.440
will appreciate how
hard it is to keep keys

00:50:14.440 --> 00:50:17.700
around for decrypting content.

00:50:17.700 --> 00:50:20.320
And then there's this
access control question

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:22.980
that keeps coming up all the time.

00:50:22.980 --> 00:50:28.070
So, some of you will have some
familiarity with the notion

00:50:28.070 --> 00:50:30.190
of containers that's
starting to come along

00:50:30.190 --> 00:50:33.550
in online cloud environment.

00:50:33.550 --> 00:50:38.560
Containers are actually kind of
