01:52:45.190 --> 01:52:48.180
for doing the datathon, actually
the second one we've done

01:52:48.180 --> 01:52:50.980
and it was really amazing over
the course of the datathon

01:52:50.980 --> 01:52:55.840
to see researchers actually using
these web archives that often,

01:52:55.840 --> 01:52:59.000
some of them I have crawled
myself entirely on a whim.

01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:05.480
So, the historical record often
is determined by areas of interest

01:53:05.480 --> 01:53:07.480
and I was like, let's
crawl every museum site

01:53:07.480 --> 01:53:09.980
and people did some awesome
stuff with the museum data.

01:53:09.980 --> 01:53:13.260
So, Wendy sort of challenged
us to do a little history,

01:53:13.260 --> 01:53:16.320
a little method, and then
a little big picture stuff

01:53:16.320 --> 01:53:17.620
in a very short time frame.

01:53:17.620 --> 01:53:19.530
So, I'm going to try to run
through it pretty quickly.

01:53:19.530 --> 01:53:22.280
So, folks that don't know
the Internet Archive,

01:53:22.280 --> 01:53:23.580
we are a nonprofit library.

01:53:23.580 --> 01:53:25.060 position:56%
We are in a church in San Francisco.

01:53:25.060 --> 01:53:26.360
It's open to the public.

01:53:26.360 --> 01:53:27.820
Please come by if you're in town.

01:53:27.820 --> 01:53:30.210
And we have been around, this
is our 20-year anniversary.

01:53:30.210 --> 01:53:32.230
So, there will be some big
events later in the year.

01:53:32.230 --> 01:53:35.620
And our mission is universal
access to all knowledge.

01:53:35.620 --> 01:53:38.270
So, we are not just an
archive of web material.

01:53:38.270 --> 01:53:40.540
We actually have lots
of digital content.

01:53:40.540 --> 01:53:42.120
You'll see all the stats there.

01:53:42.120 --> 01:53:46.190 position:56%
The one, of course, most relevant
to our talk today is our web archive

01:53:46.190 --> 01:53:49.730
which is about to hit
50 billion captures.

01:53:49.730 --> 01:53:53.880
So, we've been doing it
since the beginning in 1996.

01:53:53.880 --> 01:53:57.790
We get about a billion captures,
a capture is just a web resource,

01:53:57.790 --> 01:54:00.620
per week, and a little
over a petabyte per year

01:54:00.620 --> 01:54:02.310
in web data specifically.

01:54:02.310 --> 01:54:07.170
So, we do have 25 petabytes of
unique information of all variety,

01:54:07.170 --> 01:54:10.850
and a little over a half of
that is the web material.

01:54:10.850 --> 01:54:13.650
So, here's sort of how
our crawling and capture

01:54:13.650 --> 01:54:16.120
for web content has
gone over the years.

01:54:16.120 --> 01:54:17.960
Obviously scaled up.

01:54:17.960 --> 01:54:20.990
I didn't actually put YouTube
on there, but YouTube should be

01:54:20.990 --> 01:54:24.940
on this slide somewhere since it of
course, audio video, it's migration

01:54:24.940 --> 01:54:29.900
to the web has really expanded
storage needs for all web archives.

01:54:29.900 --> 01:54:34.630
So, our crawling I think
sometimes strikes people as being,

01:54:34.630 --> 01:54:38.170 position:56%
it's one big crawl, and the internet
archive just crawls everything.

01:54:38.170 --> 01:54:41.560 position:56%
And it's actually much more dynamic.

01:54:41.560 --> 01:54:45.760
It's much more, I have this sort of
constellation metaphor in my talk.

01:54:45.760 --> 01:54:48.560
And I'll cover a couple
of the different methods,

01:54:48.560 --> 01:54:52.120
but it's actually, I call it
multimodal crawling strategy.

01:54:52.120 --> 01:54:55.610
So, we capture in many different
ways, not just ourselves,

01:54:55.610 --> 01:54:58.400
but also working directly
with partners.

01:54:58.400 --> 01:55:02.910
We do run big global crawls, both
at a very wide and shallow level,

01:55:02.910 --> 01:55:06.620
and at a very deep and
sort of well-scoped level.

01:55:06.620 --> 01:55:07.920
So, there are global crawls.

01:55:07.920 --> 01:55:11.120
But, other things we do are
work with national libraries

01:55:11.120 --> 01:55:15.310
to capture country level
domains, so, CCTLDs.

01:55:15.310 --> 01:55:19.460
So, we worked over the years with
at least a dozen national libraries

01:55:19.460 --> 01:55:22.270
to get dot something, something.

01:55:22.270 --> 01:55:26.190
To get sort of a big capture of
a specific country's web domain.

01:55:26.190 --> 01:55:29.390
We have collaborative collections,
a couple of which I mentioned here.

01:55:29.390 --> 01:55:32.610
End of Term Web Archive, that we
do with LC and a number of others,

01:55:32.610 --> 01:55:34.320
which is capturing a snapshot

01:55:34.320 --> 01:55:37.320
of the entire US Federal
Government web domain at every,

01:55:37.320 --> 01:55:40.150
before and after every
presidential transition.

01:55:40.150 --> 01:55:41.960
We capture things like
orphan domains.

01:55:41.960 --> 01:55:44.500
People talked about the Cuba
collection, we just decided

01:55:44.500 --> 01:55:46.880 position:56%
to crawl .cu, just because we could.

01:55:46.880 --> 01:55:50.330
Spontaneous events, of
course, we're doing crawling

01:55:50.330 --> 01:55:54.360 position:56%
around the pulse event and have done
it for all sorts of global events.

01:55:54.360 --> 01:55:58.310
And the of course we work directly
with researchers, K12 institutes

01:55:58.310 --> 01:56:01.340
and partnerships with
educational programs.

01:56:01.340 --> 01:56:06.120 position:56%
And those are both to get subject
experts to contribute seeds and URLs

01:56:06.120 --> 01:56:08.220
for us to crawl and
also of course to work

01:56:08.220 --> 01:56:10.120
with them I use of our archives.

01:56:10.120 --> 01:56:14.490
Another thing I was really
enamored events talk about the need

01:56:14.490 --> 01:56:17.870
for business models, and
especially sustainability

01:56:17.870 --> 01:56:19.740
around web archiving programs,

01:56:19.740 --> 01:56:23.500
internet archive does have a quite
possible web archiving subscription

01:56:23.500 --> 01:56:28.400
service that's used by almost 500
institutions, mostly libraries

01:56:28.400 --> 01:56:32.840 position:56%
and archives, in the academic realm
to create curated special collection

01:56:32.840 --> 01:56:35.810
of archives that they
can then of course store

01:56:35.810 --> 01:56:39.910
and preserve locally themselves, as
well as provide access through IA.

01:56:39.910 --> 01:56:42.420
So, those are capture
methods, access methods.

01:56:42.420 --> 01:56:44.200
Of course, most people
are going to be familiar

01:56:44.200 --> 01:56:45.810
with the Wayback Machine.

01:56:45.810 --> 01:56:49.160
You can enter a URL and see
its capture rate over time.

01:56:49.160 --> 01:56:51.610
Of course, the obvious example is
an early capture of the Library

01:56:51.610 --> 01:56:54.080
of Congress website from 1999.

01:56:54.080 --> 01:56:56.820
It actually holds up in
this sort of web design way.

01:56:56.820 --> 01:56:59.250
So, props to LC.

01:56:59.250 --> 01:57:02.010
Of course, there's other
types of collections too.

01:57:02.010 --> 01:57:05.770
So, not just websites,
but type of web content

01:57:05.770 --> 01:57:07.400
that you can then aggregate.

01:57:07.400 --> 01:57:09.950
So, this is of course,
we just extracted a bunch

01:57:09.950 --> 01:57:12.110
of animated GIFs of puppies.

01:57:12.110 --> 01:57:15.350
Because I really truly believe that
the web would not be what it is

01:57:15.350 --> 01:57:18.010
without the ability
to share dog photos.

01:57:18.010 --> 01:57:21.180
But it also, sort of is indicative

01:57:21.180 --> 01:57:23.250
of the creative expression
that's also on the web,

01:57:23.250 --> 01:57:28.080
that we sometimes forget about when
focusing on the scholarly record.

01:57:28.080 --> 01:57:29.830
Other access models
like the hack-a-thon,

01:57:29.830 --> 01:57:32.780
or research partnerships
to get our data out there

01:57:32.780 --> 01:57:34.900
and get people using
it in different ways.

01:57:34.900 --> 01:57:36.610
So, that's access methods.

01:57:36.610 --> 01:57:39.610
And then sort of technology
and infrastructure methods,

01:57:39.610 --> 01:57:42.280
we are of course dedicated
to open source software.

01:57:42.280 --> 01:57:45.350
Heritrix as a crawler, Wayback
as the piece of software.

01:57:45.350 --> 01:57:49.200
And we are developing new methods
of crawling technology to deal

01:57:49.200 --> 01:57:52.530
with the dynamic web
in java script as well

01:57:52.530 --> 01:57:57.420 position:56%
as more API based infrastructure for
interoperability of cross systems.

01:57:57.420 --> 01:58:00.240
And so, when thinking about
opportunities and challenges,

01:58:00.240 --> 01:58:02.130
we have this thing called
the do we have it at API.

01:58:02.130 --> 01:58:05.650
And it's basically just a big
dump of all sorts of identifiers

01:58:05.650 --> 01:58:08.200
from catalogs and ISBNs and things.

01:58:08.200 --> 01:58:11.400
And we can just hit it and see
whether we have it in the archive.

01:58:11.400 --> 01:58:13.150
And I thought that was an
interesting model for thinking

01:58:13.150 --> 01:58:16.570
about what we have and what we sort
of accomplished in web archiving.

01:58:16.570 --> 01:58:19.040
And what we don't have and what
are the current challenges.

01:58:19.040 --> 01:58:22.970
So, we are content agnostic for
acquisition of web material.

01:58:22.970 --> 01:58:28.220
It's print, it's audio video, it's
code, it's CSS all kind of thing.

01:58:28.220 --> 01:58:31.950
The web has consumed
basically all methods

01:58:31.950 --> 01:58:33.970
of digital information delivery.

01:58:33.970 --> 01:58:37.980
So, things that were not ever on
the web, printed in digital form

01:58:37.980 --> 01:58:39.430
and now just going
straight to the web.

01:58:39.430 --> 01:58:42.870 position:56%
The legal issues, I think they still
exist a little bit, but have been,

01:58:42.870 --> 01:58:46.070
I think we've made incredible
progress, the whole community

01:58:46.070 --> 01:58:49.790 position:56%
over the years on this when internet
archives started, before my time,

01:58:49.790 --> 01:58:52.560
but people were like, 'oh my
God, you can't capture it.'

01:58:52.560 --> 01:58:54.210
And, 'oh my God, you
can't even replay it,

01:58:54.210 --> 01:58:56.210
how could you do that,
it's not yours.'

01:58:56.210 --> 01:58:58.780
But it is of course a
public publishing platform.

01:58:58.780 --> 01:59:02.720
And I think advocacy around access
has really grown over the years.

01:59:02.720 --> 01:59:04.100
Time travels.

01:59:04.100 --> 01:59:06.770
Obviously, we have been building
time travel into the web.

01:59:06.770 --> 01:59:10.290
There are lots of browser
plugins and methods for looking

01:59:10.290 --> 01:59:15.780
at archival replays of web
content over time in a way

01:59:15.780 --> 01:59:18.420
that is very familiar to
browsing the live web.

01:59:18.420 --> 01:59:21.200
Collaborative models,
some technical stuff.

01:59:21.200 --> 01:59:23.840 position:56%
We do de-duplicate content in cases.

01:59:23.840 --> 01:59:27.130
We do actually do and crawl
RSS feeds, every link added

01:59:27.130 --> 01:59:29.590
to Wikipedia, every blogger entry.

01:59:29.590 --> 01:59:33.390
Lots of other methods that
we get automatic URL feeds

01:59:33.390 --> 01:59:35.230
that go right into the crawlers.

01:59:35.230 --> 01:59:37.690
And lots of automation
around crawling activities.

01:59:37.690 --> 01:59:40.760
So, the web has become much more
dynamic, interactive, scrolling,

01:59:40.760 --> 01:59:43.320
clicking, and we're of
course trying to build bots

01:59:43.320 --> 01:59:45.700
to do that behavior at scale.

01:59:45.700 --> 01:59:48.230
And then emulation which
Vint also talked about.

01:59:48.230 --> 01:59:49.790
What have we not been
doing so great?

01:59:49.790 --> 01:59:51.880
The web has been moving
of course more and more

01:59:51.880 --> 01:59:53.180
to a programming environment.

01:59:53.180 --> 01:59:54.720
It's not static documents.

01:59:54.720 --> 01:59:57.980
It's interactions, it's
replay, it's behaviors.

01:59:57.980 --> 01:59:59.790
And those are very
challenging to capture

01:59:59.790 --> 02:00:03.230
with our traditional
archival methods.

02:00:03.230 --> 02:00:05.940
APIfication, Wild Gardens,
Cloud Computing.

02:00:05.940 --> 02:00:08.700
These are all mostly
inaccessible except

02:00:08.700 --> 02:00:13.270
for with human intermediation,
or passwords or other methods.

02:00:13.270 --> 02:00:14.740
So, that could really
limit the amount

02:00:14.740 --> 02:00:16.260
of content we're able to capture.

02:00:16.260 --> 02:00:18.090
Interoperability, we're
getting there,

02:00:18.090 --> 02:00:20.450
but a lot of web archiving
systems don't necessarily talk

02:00:20.450 --> 02:00:24.870
to each other very well, or require
very centralized infrastructure

02:00:24.870 --> 02:00:26.370
to operate.

02:00:26.370 --> 02:00:29.780
And then bulk access is challenging
at the scale in which we operate,

02:00:29.780 --> 02:00:32.060
which is the multi petabyte scale.

02:00:32.060 --> 02:00:35.430
And making resources available
for training and education,

02:00:35.430 --> 02:00:39.030
and how things were captured
or how you can work with them.

02:00:39.030 --> 02:00:42.310
So, in looking at these sorts
of areas of archival activity.

02:00:42.310 --> 02:00:45.410
So, I come from an archiving
background, and I always try

02:00:45.410 --> 02:00:48.770
to think of web archiving within
the traditional archival endeavor.

02:00:48.770 --> 02:00:52.080
And you sort of have these three
modes of Selection, capture

02:00:52.080 --> 02:00:54.980
and management, and access
which have not just code

02:00:54.980 --> 02:00:58.320
and technology involved, but
of course communities as well.

02:00:58.320 --> 02:01:01.890
And so, when you sort of
think about networking

02:01:01.890 --> 02:01:04.780
between these different
areas of operation,

02:01:04.780 --> 02:01:08.570
and maybe prescript your slide with
a certain model, it actually starts

02:01:08.570 --> 02:01:14.050
to look quite similar to the
original technical diagram of TCP.

02:01:14.050 --> 02:01:17.570
So, I've been thinking a
lot as a web history nerd,

02:01:17.570 --> 02:01:19.780
of sort of the successes
of the internet

02:01:19.780 --> 02:01:23.340
and Vint spoke much more
eloquently to this than I will.

02:01:23.340 --> 02:01:26.580
But what made the internet such
the incredible amazing thing

02:01:26.580 --> 02:01:29.220
that has just sort of
conquered the world.

02:01:29.220 --> 02:01:32.430
And what can we, when building web
archiving, web organic programs

02:01:32.430 --> 02:01:36.160
and technologies take some
of those key themes out.

02:01:36.160 --> 02:01:38.640
And so, Vint talked
about the modulization,

02:01:38.640 --> 02:01:42.370 position:56%
the distributed nature, the
portability and flexibility of a lot

02:01:42.370 --> 02:01:44.740
of the technical systems
and protocols.

02:01:44.740 --> 02:01:46.430
I think the social construction

02:01:46.430 --> 02:01:48.830
of the internet's evolution
was very important.

02:01:48.830 --> 02:01:54.710 position:56%
It was not just producers creating
for users, the producers were users.

02:01:54.710 --> 02:01:57.780
And that innovation was dispersed
around a social community

02:01:57.780 --> 02:02:01.660
that was both informal and
you know very feedback driven.

02:02:01.660 --> 02:02:04.570
And of course, it was
built for scalability

02:02:04.570 --> 02:02:06.650
for gateway between networks.

02:02:06.650 --> 02:02:08.630
And for great fault tolerance.

02:02:08.630 --> 02:02:11.270
And we can sort of adapt some
of these to web archiving.

02:02:11.270 --> 02:02:14.440
We are trying to modularize
crawling, not just in the global

02:02:14.440 --> 02:02:18.200
and little special,
and domain style,

02:02:18.200 --> 02:02:20.150
but also the methods of capture.

02:02:20.150 --> 02:02:24.890
Proxy browsing, traditional
crawling, user interaction,

02:02:24.890 --> 02:02:29.650
archival replay, and capture
while you actually browse.

02:02:29.650 --> 02:02:33.200
Making WARCs and metadata
more portable between systems.

02:02:33.200 --> 02:02:36.470
The work is something of
a heterogenous format.

02:02:36.470 --> 02:02:39.630
But then also building on
the lessons of the early net

02:02:39.630 --> 02:02:43.610
for social construction, community
models, coordinated collecting,

02:02:43.610 --> 02:02:46.990
collaborations with K
through 12 programs as well

02:02:46.990 --> 02:02:51.100
as academic researchers, and
then systems of interoperability

02:02:51.100 --> 02:02:53.510
and multiplicity of access models.

02:02:53.510 --> 02:02:56.190
And so, I always try to
close talks with sort

02:02:56.190 --> 02:02:58.430
of what are the big
preservation imperatives.

02:02:58.430 --> 02:03:01.450
I think we wanted to go big and
keep in mind for this conference

02:03:01.450 --> 02:03:05.120
at least, if we're going to
work to save the web at scale,

02:03:05.120 --> 02:03:07.850
what are sort of our
motivating factors.

02:03:07.850 --> 02:03:10.450
And I do think, obviously,
I think as most of us do,

02:03:10.450 --> 02:03:14.230
the web is the most significant
communication platform of our era,

02:03:14.230 --> 02:03:17.570
so we are living in a very unique
historical moment that has a piece

02:03:17.570 --> 02:03:23.120 position:56%
of technology that has changed a lot
of how, not just how we buy things

02:03:23.120 --> 02:03:25.400
and interact and socialize,

02:03:25.400 --> 02:03:29.190
but really the whole sort
of landscape of society.

02:03:29.190 --> 02:03:32.710
It also marks an unprecedented
confluence of ease of publication

02:03:32.710 --> 02:03:34.710
and ease of archival acquisition.

02:03:34.710 --> 02:03:37.830
So, archives used to have to go out
and get things, or pay for them,

02:03:37.830 --> 02:03:42.030
or work with donors to get them,
and it was very action driven.

02:03:42.030 --> 02:03:46.250
And things were published and they
were sort of in some remote world.

02:03:46.250 --> 02:03:49.200
But we're in this unique moment
where you can both make a blog

02:03:49.200 --> 02:03:52.060
and you can archive it
within seconds essentially.

02:03:52.060 --> 02:03:54.950
So, that's a very unique
characteristic

02:03:54.950 --> 02:03:56.250
of our moment of time.

02:03:56.250 --> 02:03:59.440
It also, I think as David
and Ian both spoke to,

02:03:59.440 --> 02:04:03.030
allows for this unprecedented
plurality of representation

02:04:03.030 --> 02:04:05.330
within the historical record.

02:04:05.330 --> 02:04:08.510
You know, traditionally,
archives were very much motivated

02:04:08.510 --> 02:04:12.280
by power, or wealth.

02:04:12.280 --> 02:04:18.540 position:56%
So, the folks captured in the
archives were often people that were

02:04:18.540 --> 02:04:21.350
of power and wealth
and of a certain class.

02:04:21.350 --> 02:04:23.840
And it was very difficult to
necessarily capture the day

02:04:23.840 --> 02:04:27.680 position:56%
to day lives of average citizens and
that's really changed with the web.

02:04:27.680 --> 02:04:30.900
And then the last one is just the
sort of great motivating factor,

02:04:30.900 --> 02:04:34.880
that as Wendy also mentioned
are our moment in time,

02:04:34.880 --> 02:04:36.700
where we can archive its scale

02:04:36.700 --> 02:04:40.130
and get this amazing
diverse record will be very,

02:04:40.130 --> 02:04:43.500
very brief in the soft
of technological arc.

